## 11. ASYNC RUST MISTAKES

### Flaw: Forgetting About Task Cancellation

**Description:** AI generates async code that assumes tasks always run to completion, putting cleanup logic after await points where it may never execute if the task is cancelled.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
async fn my_task(counter: Arc<AtomicUsize>) {
    counter.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
    do_work().await;
    counter.fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Relaxed);  // May never run if task cancelled
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
async fn my_task(counter: Arc<AtomicUsize>) {
    counter.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
    let _guard = scopeguard::guard((), |_| {
        counter.fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
    });
    do_work().await;
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Task cancellation is an implicit contract in async Rust that has no direct analog in most other languages. AI generates code with implicit "happy path" assumptions.

**Impact:** Resource leaks, incorrect state, counter drift.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

---

### Flaw: `select!` in Loops Creating and Destroying Futures

**Description:** Using `select!` in a loop recreates futures on every iteration, potentially losing buffered data.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
loop {
    tokio::select! {
        _ = abort_signal.recv() => return,
        msg = connection.recv() => {  // Future recreated each iteration
            process(msg).await;
        }
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
let abort = abort_signal.recv().fuse();
pin_mut!(abort);

loop {
    tokio::select! {
        _ = &mut abort => return,
        msg = connection.recv() => {
            process(msg).await;
        }
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The "simple" select-in-loop pattern looks correct and often works for simple cases. The subtle issue of future recreation and data loss requires deep async expertise.

**Impact:** Lost messages, data corruption, non-deterministic behavior under load.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

---

### Flaw: Future Progress Starvation

**Description:** AI generates async code where one future blocks others from making progress.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
async fn serve(listener: TcpListener) {
    loop {
        let (stream, _) = listener.accept().await.unwrap();
        handle_connection(stream).await;  // Blocks accepting new connections
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
async fn serve(listener: TcpListener) {
    loop {
        let (stream, _) = listener.accept().await.unwrap();
        tokio::spawn(async move {
            handle_connection(stream).await;
        });
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Sequential processing looks "correct" and simpler. AI doesn't reason about concurrent throughput.

**Impact:** Server handles only one connection at a time. Dropped connections, missed heartbeats under load.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

---

### Flaw: Holding RAII Guards Across Await Points

**Description:** AI holds resource pool connections or other RAII objects across await points, starving the resource pool.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
async fn fetch_and_process(pool: &Pool) {
    let mut conn = pool.get().await.unwrap();
    let data = sqlx::query("SELECT * FROM items")
        .fetch_all(&mut conn).await.unwrap();
    for item in data {
        expensive_processing(item).await;  // Connection held entire time
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
async fn fetch_and_process(pool: &Pool) {
    let data = {
        let mut conn = pool.get().await.unwrap();
        sqlx::query("SELECT * FROM items")
            .fetch_all(&mut conn).await.unwrap()
    };  // Connection returned to pool here
    for item in data {
        expensive_processing(item).await;
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The "fetch then process" pattern naturally keeps the connection alive. Explicit scoping for early resource release requires understanding resource pool semantics.

**Impact:** Pool exhaustion, connection timeouts, cascading failures.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

